Doing my CVMA race report a little different, because after nearly 5 years, I'm saying goodbye to my beloved R3, Willow. 

This little bike has taken me on an incredible journey, & taught me so much. My goal was always to be able to master this bike to the point that I could run a 2 flat lap time at @chuckwallavalleyraceway 💛 & this past weekend I accomplished that mission. As I took my last lap on Willow, I said my goodbyes, thanked her for all the memories, & for leading me to a 2nd place win in the Expert 350 SS Championship 🏆

I couldn't have done any of this without my ultimate coach, cheerleader, pit crew, and trophy guy @zedex_tenahr ❤️ I can't put to words the gratitude I have for you and the way you have pushed me towards my goals and supported me through everything both on and off the track. I'm always winning with you by my side, and I esky esky love you! 

To all the sponsors that I have had to support me on this journey thank you, thank you, thank you. It's companies like you supporting racers that continue to give life to this sport. 

•Jesse of @nortonmotorsports 🛠️ from the very beginning you have helped me turn a humble little street bike into a racing machine, and I'm so thankful for all your help and guidance.

2023/2024 CVMA ROUND 3 Race Report: 
This round was definitely about overcoming. From overcoming breaking my finger last round, to continued suspension issues, to finding it within myself to even want to race anymore. I was reminded why this is the greatest sport & why you can just never give up. 

Saturday: everyone seems to be in a strange mood. Coupled with overcast weather, & everyone seeming to have concerns about crashing, by the time it was my turn to race I remember turning to Alex & saying I just really didn't want to. But I sucked it up went out for my formula 40 race & had my usual solid launch & was able to cinch a first place without any issues. Although still not going sub 2 min, I'm proud of myself for getting out there even when I wasn't feeling it. 

Sunday: The weather was much improved. I was feeling pumped to race although mine was literally the very last race of the day. I got to spend the majority of the day focusing on my love @zedex_tenahr &  being the best pit bitch that I could be. Was super proud of him & excited for his continued improvements on both his ZX10R & the Indian. Taking home PR's & trophies, I could have ended the weekend there & been extremely excited. But I still had work to do. Unfortunately right before my race I ended up crushing my broken finger again by accident leaving it throbbing in my glove when it was time to go out for my race. It certainly affected my launch, & going from a P3 position on the grid to last place into T1, I had settled on the fact that I needed to just be patient & wait for opportunities to pick off my competitors. But after training with the amazing Patricia Fernandez I made short work of that & moved back into first position by T14 & I was able to maintain 1st for the remainder of the race. As well as knock off a few laps at a 1:59 pace! It was a good reminder to myself to never give up & to never count myself out. 

I never thought that I would be the racer that all my competitors were trying to catch. But as I continue to prove that I can do this & I have earned my first place in the championship, I'll continue to put on those burners and keep my competitors nipping at my heels. 🏆
Very Merry Christmas to all our friends and family.🎄🎅🏽 We hope you have a wonderful day of celebrating! ❤️- A-Team
